            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Mr Editor</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In your <date>April</date> number, there appears<lb/> a
                communication, from <placeName>California</placeName> over the signature of<lb/>
                    “<hi rend="underline"><persName>Theophilus</persName></hi>” relating to affairs
                in that distant part of<lb/> the Union, which from his statement appears to be
                every<lb/> thing but what they should be, Among other things he<lb/>
                <del>says</del> avers that “<persName>Dr. Henry</persName> then refused to make more
                proselytes,”<lb/> and then <del>proceeds and</del> continues says “Two
                    <add>כהנים</add> applied to the Congre=<lb/>=gation Shearith Israel to be
                married to widows having<lb/> no children, which <persName>Dr Henry</persName>
                refused to do, as he<lb/> stated that the widows must have <add>כהנים</add>.”</p>
            <p>And after continuing his bill of complaints in the same<lb/> style, finished by
                envoking your attention “to the right<lb/> minded Israelites of
                        <placeName><sic>Calafernia</sic></placeName>” Which you in a very kind<lb/>
                and Philanthropic manner proceed so to do, much no doubt,<lb/> to your own
                satisfaction, but perhaps without that strict<lb/>
                <sic>reguard</sic> to the law which the question required. Where do<lb/> you find
                any such a law as “The marriage of the two <add>כהנים</add> is illegal.”<lb/>
                Certainly not in the Even Haezer V 1 the place quoted by<lb/> you in your <hi
                    rend="underline">note</hi>, and sir could you find it in any<lb/> other place,
                perhaps not, and not content with simply<lb/> answering the question propounded, you
                say “it would be the same if<lb/> simple Israelites” Now no such a law as that can
                be found<lb/> in any book of standard authority among any Israelitish<lb/> authors
                in the known world, and why and for what</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>purpose do you answer “the right minded” people<lb/> in that manner, when you know,
                if you know any<lb/> thing about the matter at all, that in the way the case<lb/>
                was stated, that there could be no objection to the marriage<lb/> of the widows to
                the two <add>חליצה</add> or to any other two Israelites.</p>
            <p>“That a <persName>Cohen</persName> is prohibited from marrying a <hi rend="underline"
                    >Chabuzah</hi>”<lb/> as stated by you, with reference to the Iben Heazer
                V.1<lb/> is a most singular thing, for the word <hi rend="underline">Chabuzah</hi>
                is not<lb/> mentioned in that place and as to the word, perhaps you<lb/> would have
                done much better in your “Note” if you had<lb/> told the “right minded” correctly
                where it is to be found<lb/> or what is the meaning of the word, but Mr Editor<lb/>
                things both in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> and
                    <placeName>California</placeName> appear to<lb/> be much out of place, in one
                place a <hi rend="underline">Dr</hi> refuses “to make<lb/> any <hi rend="underline"
                    >more</hi> proselytes” while in the other an Editor refers<lb/> to places and
                laws not to be found, and writes about<lb/> a “Chabuzah” which puts all his numerous
                readers on<lb/> tip toe of expectation hoping that in his next number<lb/>
                <del>that</del> he will tell them where the law is to be found which<lb/> forbids a
                childless widow from being married without <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> and the meaning of
                the word Chabuzah.</p>
            <p rend="indent(12)">
                <persName role="author">S. A.</persName>
            </p>
            <p>Private</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Can you insert the above in <date>May</date> No</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">Simon Ahahams M.d</persName>
            </p>
